Graphs to show the rise in rent cost in Cincinnati.

Original graphs

price_names <- c("Housing < $100",
                 "Housing $100 - $199",
                 "Housing $200 - $299",
                 "Housing $300 - $399",
                 "Housing $400 - $499",
                 "Housing $500 - $599",
                 "Housing $600 - $699",

poo2019 %>% 
      mutate(variable = factor(variable, levels = price_names)) %>%
      ggplot(aes(x=variable,y=estimate))+
      geom_col() +
      coord_flip()+
      labs(x = "Rent Price", 
       y = "Number of Individuals", 
       title = "Housing Prices in Cincinnati - 2019") +
      geom_text(aes(label = estimate), 
            hjust = -0.2, 
            vjust = 0.5, 
            color = "black", 
            size = 3)

poo2020 %>% 
      mutate(variable = factor(variable, levels = price_names)) %>%

Quick ideas

You can adjust the dimensions of your figures in the code chunk statement. This can be helpful if you have a certain size space that you want your graph to fit in on a slide.

It is probably more helpful when you make the dimensions relatively small. This has the effect of making fonts, graphics bigger and can improve clarity in the image that you actually put into a presentation.
